##"If it really works, let's do it again. " | in-depth report

Wechat Bqshenyidu

Features, Beijing Youth Daily, the official public number

Reporter / Guo Huimin, Qu Chang, Dai Youqing intern reporter / Li Yiming, Long Tianyin

Editor / Ji Weiwei

Jiangxia District Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine is donating plasma after being discharged from the hospital

On February 13, Liu Yujing of Jiangxia District Hospital of Traditional Chinese Medicine in Wuhan learned from the Deputy Director, i and 18 other rehabilitation staff of the hospital's blood donation "all have antibodies, separated from the plasma mostly used for the treatment of critically ill patients in Jiangxia District, part of the support of the Golden Pool Hospital" . Although still not clear about the final effect of plasma treatment, Liu Yujing or for this "hope" feel happy.

On the same day, the Chinese Medicine China Biology (hereinafter referred to as China Biology) announced that it had completed the collection of plasma from some of the rehabilitated persons, successfully prepared special immune plasma for clinical treatment, and treated two critical patients with special immune plasma, there are now more than 10 critical patients with follow-up treatment.

On February 14, Zhang Dingyu, director of Wuhan's Golden Pond Hospital, said that four patients in the hospital had received plasma treatment from convalescent patients and saw signs of improvement in the short term, with their vital signs gradually stabilising and their mental condition improving, "At present, it is mainly used in critically ill patients, and the clinical effect in critically ill patients is uncertain. "

Up to now, there are still many challenges in the treatment of plasma immunity. Huang Bo, vice-president of the Chinese Society of Immunology, said in an in-depth interview that how to screen patients with high neutralizing antibody content of the cured plasma, still remains to be studied. Taulina, a senior vaccine expert, also pointed out in an interview that at present the new guangte immune plasma comes from the convalescent, but how to guarantee the production of the immune plasma is a big problem.

Xu Ping, head nurse at Jiangxia District Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine, had a new idea after learning that her donated plasma could be used clinically. Later this month, she will travel to Jiangxia District's Shelter Hospital to attend to the comfort and companionship of new crown patients. There, Xu hopes to educate more patients about the treatment and participate in plasma donation, as "they are all very promising. ".

Jiangxia District Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine is donating plasma from its convalescent staff

The first plasma donors were recovered medical staff

Xu Ping was a head nurse at Jiangxia District Hospital of Traditional Chinese Medicine in Wuhan and one of the first donors of the special-free Plasma.

On January 20, Xu Ping was dizzy at work, then found a lung infection during a CT scan and was admitted to our hospital for treatment. Before the Jiangxia District Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine was set up as a designated hospital for new coronary pneumonia, more than 40 medical staff were infected with new coronary pneumonia. The hospital staff said that at present, "It is difficult to determine completely the route of infection. " Liu Yujing, who works in hospital administration, is one of those infected.

"I still don't know exactly how it got infected. " On January 16, Ms. Liu felt her temperature was abnormal and went for a CT scan. She found a shadow in her lungs. A week later, she had a nucleic acid test to confirm the diagnosis of new coronary pneumonia.

Xu recalled that she had taken and injected antiviral and immune enhancing drugs, including ceftriaxone, albumin and Moxifloxacin, as well as traditional Chinese medicine for clearing away heat and detoxication during her hospitalization. Liu Yujing is "the first day to boil the Chinese medicine, after not broken, " in addition to take Oseltamivir and other Western medicine, and injection anti-inflammatory drugs, symptoms reduced after the adoption of treatment methods such as atomization.

In the absence of a specific drug, Liu Yujing believes that the ultimate recovery is due to self-conditioning, "We have to eat more, keep in a good mood and form a virtuous circle between body and mind, " Zhang Dingyu, director of Wuhan's Golden Pond Hospital, told the media, through the body's resistance and immune regulation, can kill the virus, and thus be repaired. On January 28, Xu Ping was discharged from the hospital. Six days later, Liu Yujing was also discharged.

During his hospital stay, Xiong Kan, director of the Jiangxia District Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine, set up a wechat group for all hospital staff to boost morale. On February 4, a special message came from the group: There are now many seriously ill patients, their only hope is to inject the plasma of the convalescent carrying antibodies, so the initiative to donate plasma from the convalescent.

"I had never known about plasma therapy before, " says Xu. Soon, a colleague in the group sent a news screenshot, reported that SARS period also used plasma treatment. Rather than mobilizing ordinary patients to come back and donate plasma, Xu felt she was better suited to be the first donor.

According to Liu Yujing's understanding, the hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine was the first hospital to conduct plasma collection. The plasma donation plan was determined after the hospital communicated with the First People's Hospital in Jiangxia district. "The director said that the effect of the treatment is uncertain, but I think if there is hope to save people, donate, " Ms. Liu said. "If it really works, let's donate again. "

On Feb. 5, the first group of doctors and nurses, including Xu Ping and Liu Yujing, came to the hospital from their homes to donate plasma. Liu Bende, business director of the First People's Hospital in Jiangxia district, told health care workers who donated plasma that blood samples were taken mainly to extract antibodies for testing to see if they were effective.

Each donor's plasma collection takes 30 minutes, and the blood volume standard is 300 milliliters for women and 400 milliliters for men. "But both male colleagues chose to donate 550 milliliters, and each colleague wishes to donate more, " Xu said.

On Feb. 13, when Liu Yujing asked about the results of plasma donation on Wechat Group, the Vice Dean replied: "All of them have antibodies. Most of the plasma isolated is used to help the critically ill patients in Jiangxia District, and some of them support Jinyintan hospital. " The same day, "The plasma of 19 people in TCM hospitals will be used for the treatment of critically ill patients, " Xu said in a news report. "We are happy as long as the donated plasma can help the patients. "

To get more people to know about the plasma treatment

On February 14, Xu Ping signed up to support Jiangxia District's shelter hospital, where she will attend to new patients at the end of the month. Because of the transition from mild to severe cases of NCP, some patients develop fear and need to be accompanied and shared by a health care provider who has a healing experience, telling them that this is a necessary process.

There, Xu hopes to educate more patients about the treatment and participate in plasma donation, as "they are all very promising. ".

On the same day as the news of "special free plasma for Clinical Treatment" was released, the China Biological Union Wuhan Blood Center released a proposal for plasma donation for the recovered.

In addition to Wuhan, Guangdong, Shanxi, Jiangsu and other places have also welcomed the donation of plasma rehabilitation.

Six of the 28 people recovered from new pneumonia who were discharged from hospitals in Shanghai on the 14th are willing to donate, and one patient is already being prepared for plasma treatment, said Lu Hongzhou, a member of the Expert Group of the National Health Commission, according to thepaper.cn, detailed plans have been drawn up and staffing and instrumentation are in place. On the same day, the first antibody therapy was successfully carried out in the affiliated Hospital of Xuzhou Medical University.

Yang Xiaoming, general director of the research team set up by Chinese biology, told the media on February 15 that the plasma therapy of rehabilitees is not aimed at all new patients, but "mainly at the heavy and critical types. ". At present, the number of critically ill patients and high mortality rate, and rehabilitation of more than 6000 patients, far more than critically ill patients.

In a deep interview, the new coronary pneumonia patients plasma collection point staff said that from the evening of 13, the collection point phone kept ringing, "the exact number received is not clear, at least 40 or 50. "

Duan Kai, general manager of the Wuhan Institute of Biological Products, said in an interview that as of March 15, more than 280 registered calls had been received, more than 20 had expressed their willingness to donate, and three donors had completed the collection.

The Wuhan Blood Center staff said that the plasma collection has certain requirements for donors, to meet the age of 18 to 60 years old, confirmed infection has been COVID-19, after discharge from the hospital in good health, no other discomfort. A single donation of plasma ranges from 200 ML to 400 ml, "blood is 55 percent plasma and 45 percent blood cells. After plasma donation, the blood cells are returned to the donor. After some warm water is added, the blood can recover quickly and there will be no side effects on the donor. " The collection time is about 20 to 30 minutes, you can donate again after 14 days.

Zhang Dingyu, director of Jinyintan Hospital, said in an earlier interview that he hoped the donation would continue. At the same time, he stressed that there are risks to the plasma treatment, as it may contain allergies or other uncertainties because it is someone else's plasma, "But in a life-saving environment, it is a necessary option for the treatment of critically ill patients, and the risks are far less than the benefits. "

A recovered person in Shanxi donates blood plasma (photo / Taiyuan Red Cross Blood Center) 

There are still some problems to be solved in the treatment of immunity plasma

Huang Bo, vice president of the Chinese Society of Immunology, said in a once-in-an-lifetime interview that patients with new coronavirus pneumonia recovered not through injections and drugs, but through the activation of the body's immune system, which enabled the virus to be eliminated. "One of the most powerful weapons in our immune system is the activation of b cells to produce antibodies. "

According to Huang Bo, the medical principle of immune plasma is that there will be antibody production in the recovered patient's body, which is produced by the activation of B cells in the body and released to the outside of the cell, and then into the blood, so the antibody exists in the blood. By infusing antibody-containing plasma into the patient, the antibodies in the convalescent plasma can be used to fight the virus in the patient's body.

As for the specific process by which antibodies work, Huang says, viruses become viable only after they enter a cell, and the antibodies bind to the virus to prevent it from entering the cell, in which case, the virus degrades itself over time. "antibody levels in the plasma of different convalescent patients are not consistent, some are high and some are low, so we need to screen them, and it would be better to use high antibody levels to treat them. "

In Huang Bo's view, plasma therapy still faces some challenges. Antibodies include neutralizing antibodies (which are produced when a pathogen invades the body) and non-neutralizing antibodies, both of which work when antibodies in the plasma of the recovered person are used to fight the disease, but there are some differences in the mechanism of confrontation. "there are more types of non-neutralizing antibodies than neutralizing antibodies, and screening the plasma of cured patients with high neutralizing antibodies remains a major challenge in the treatment process. "

Taulina, a senior vaccine expert, said in an in-depth interview that the new coronavirus immune plasma another problem to be solved is the production. At present, the new crown immunity comes from the convalescent, but the product immunity can not come from the convalescent, because this source is not stable and can not be collected repeatedly. In addition, the concentration of antibody in the body of each recovered person is different, so the concentration of antibody in the new coronaviruses after extraction may not be exactly quantifiable.

"If you use too much, you waste precious plasma, and if you use too little, it can be even worse, " Dr. Taulina said. In studies of SARS survivors' plasma to suppress the SARS virus, a "ADE effect, " in which antibodies actually enhance infection, had been found. Specific antibodies can bind to the virus to make it lose its ability to adhere to prevent the virus from infecting the body. In some cases, however, the antibodies bind to the virus and help it enter the cell, making it more infectious.

"Ade usually occurs when the antibody concentration is low. That is, if you don't give the patient enough immunity, there is a possibility that it will worsen the disease, " Taurina said.

(at the request of the interviewee, Xu Ping and Liu Yujing were given pseudonyms.)
